passages.text: Toronto-Dominion Bank

Adjusted EPS exceeded consensus on lower- than- modeled PCLs and higher- than- expected fee revenue while expenses and NII were modestly worse than expected. Credit normalization continued with GILs up \(10\%\) and formations \(20\%\) higher. CET1 ratio declined 10bps to \(14.8\%\) with a buyback of 16mn shares.

Adjusted EPS beat: TD reported EPS of C\(1.89 in 3Q25. Adjusted for several one- time items, EPS was C\)2.20. Consensus was C\(2.05. It posted a return on RWA of 2.06% (2.40% adjusted) and ROTCE of 13.6% (15.8% adjusted). Book value rose slightly to C\)67.13 (1.6x). Adjusted revenue rose 10% y- o- y. Its CET1 ratio declined 10bps to 14.8%. Average diluted share count decreased 1.3%.

Notables: It noted C\(262bn (\)0.13) balance sheet restructuring charges, C\(333mn restructuring charges (C\)0.14), C\(32mn (C\)0.01) acquisition and integration charges, C\(55mn (\)0.02) from terminated FHN- related hedges and C\(33mn (\)0.01) intangible amortization.

Restructuring: TD updated its expense restructuring program expected to deliver C\(550mn- C\)650mn pre- tax annual savings with \~C\(100mn to be realized in F2025. It also expects an \~2% reduction in headcount. Still, it expects to incur total restructuring charges of C\)600mn- C\(700mn pre- tax over several quarters (C\)496mn recorded in 2025 ytd).

NII higher: Net interest income rose 5% from 2Q25, reflecting three higher days in the quarter and volume growth in Canadian Personal and Commercial Banking, higher revenue from treasury and balance sheet activities and the impact of balance sheet restructuring activities and higher deposit margins in U.S. Retail.
NIM expands: TD's NIM rose 6bps to 1.82% (+12bp y- o- y). On an adjusted basis, its NIM was 1.83% (+5bps q- q). Average earning assets declined 2%.
Loans flat: Period- end loans were relatively unchanged. Business and government loans decline 3.6%, resi mortgage decreased 0.1%, while consumer gained 5.1% and card rose 2.8%.
Deposits lower: Deposits decreased 0.9% from 2Q25, with decreases in business and government and personal term partially offset by an increase in personal non- term deposits.
Please see analyst certifications and important disclosures beginning on page 3. Completed: 28- Aug- 25, 13:06 GMT Released: 28- Aug- 25, 13:06 GMT Restricted - External

**Fee income higher:** Adjusted non-interest income rose 1% from 1Q25, driven by increases in US Retail and Wealth Management & Insurance.

**Costs higher sequentially:** Adjusted expenses increased 3% q-o-q and rose 132% y-o-y with 1/4 of the y-o-y growth driven by variable compensation, FX and Strategic Card Partners. It expects F2025 expense growth at the upper end of the 5-7% range (assuming F2024 levels of variable compensation, FX and SCP).
**PCLs lower:** PCLs dropped 28% to C$971mn. Its PCL ratio declined 17bps to 41bps.
**GILs higher:** GILs rose 9.6% sequentially to C$5.334bn. Its GIL ratio increased 5bps to 55bps. GIL formations were C$2.433bn, up 20% from 2Q25.
